orts keyword search and ﬁltering, the absence of semantic search and AI-enhanced \ndiscovery may limit its utility for non-technical roles, such as call center representatives. Conﬂuence's \nAI features, though present, primarily enhance core functionalities rather than offering specialized KM \nadvancements.\nIn Knowledge Authoring (7/10), Conﬂuence shines with its array of templates and real-time collaborative \nediting. Yet, it falls short in metadata management and notably underperforms in handling attachments, \nincluding video and audio ﬁles, impacting content organization and accessibility. This limitation under-\nscores a gap in comprehensive content management and ﬁndability. \nTechnical Performance & Innovation (8/10) illustrates its commitment to maintaining a scalable and \nadaptive platform with room for growth in pioneering technologies. Minimal Reporting & Analytics (6/10) \nindicates a need for more profound insights and analytics capabilities to enhance knowledge manage-\nment decision-making processes.\nThe platform's most notable strength lies in its Collaboration (9/10) features, afﬁrming that it is a pow-\nerful tool for team-based project execution and knowledge sharing. This focus on collaborative features \nand its capacity to integrate with all Atlassian products and various SaaS platforms for business chat, \ndiagramming, and data visualization enriches this platform as a knowledge-sharing ecosystem. Strong \nCustomer Support (8/10) ensures adequate technical and tactical assistance, facilitating it as a self-ser-\nvice model.\nUltimately, Conﬂuence presents a solid option for knowledge management with an overall score of 7.9 \nout of 10. It balances its extensive collaborative tools and the need for advancements in analytics, search, \nand AI features. This evaluation encourages organizations to consider Conﬂuence's potent collaboration \ncapabilities against desired KM sophistication. \nAtlassian Conﬂuence is known for its strong collaboration and knowledge management features, which \nare particularly suited for agile and tech-savvy teams. It is chosen for its user-friendly interface, exten-\nsive template library, and seamless integration with Jira.\nPROS CONS\nExcellent collaboration tools and integration \nwith Atlassian products\nLimited search and discovery capabilities\nUser-friendly interface and rich template \noptions\nChallenges in handling attachments \nStrong support for mobile and desktop devic-\nes\nPoor metadata management\nConﬂuence\nReviews\nWhat do you like best about Conﬂuence?\nCan create a page for each meeting that I have with my team and tag people's names on the page \n(so they receive notiﬁcations/updates for the page). Can get a notiﬁcation for when a page is edited. \nGood for in-house documentation (wiki).\nWhat do you dislike about Conﬂuence?\nIf there are a lot of pages in a category tree, it's hard to ﬁnd a page. You can use the search bar, but the \nsearch bar isn't helpful for pages whose titles have been renamed.\nWhat do you like best about Conﬂuence?\nThe real-time editing capabilities and collaborative features make it easy for our team to work togeth-\ner on documents, plans, and ideas. One of Conﬂuence's standout features is its intuitive content cre-\nation tools. Whether it's creating detailed documentation, meeting notes, or project plans, the plat-\nform's editor is user-friendly and allows for rich formatting. The integration capabilities of Conﬂuence \nare impressive. Seamless integration with JIRA and other tools in the Atlassian ecosystem, as well as \na wide range of third-party apps, has streamlined our workﬂows.\nWhat do you dislike about Conﬂuence?\nSimilar to JIRA, Conﬂuence has a slight learning curve, especially for new users. Conﬂuence's editor \nis user-friendly, but I ﬁnd it somewhat limited. Enhanced formatting features could cater to users with \nmore sophisticated document layout requirements. For example, it's quite impossible to manage E